Hi @egemenozkan!

The `$r` is already a jQuery object of the table row. So, yes you can use jQuery.

I would recommend not using `dataset` because it's [not supported in IE < 10](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/HTML/Using_data_attributes#Issues). Instead try this:

```js
var filterFunctions = {
  2 : function(e, n, f, i, $r, c, data) {
    var packageId = $r.attr('data-package');
    $('tr.package_'+ packageId).hide();
    return true;
  }
}
```

Hi @CiTRO33!

Hmm, maybe the easiest solution would be to remove the blur event listener ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/856bzzeL/1377/)):

```js
$(function () {
	$('table').tablesorter({
		theme: 'blue',
		widgets: ['zebra', 'filter'],
		widgetOptions: {
			filter_liveSearch: false
		},
    initialized: function(table) {
    	var namespace = table.config.namespace + 'filter';
    	$(table).find('.tablesorter-filter').off('blur' + namespace);
    }
	});
});
```

